Abstract: Theories from several disciplines are integrated into a general model for the prediction of a national propensity to expropriate foreign private direct investments in less-developed host countries. A discriminant analysis is used to test the hypothesis that the presence of such instability combined with a high level of foreign (American) investments will result in a high propensity to expropriate. The model is tested empirically on Latin American data from the 1968&ndash;71 period, and the main hypothesis confirmed.&copy; 1974 JIBS. Journal of International Business Studies (1974) 5, 51&ndash;71
